memoriam tuam: a remarkable memory is attributed to Caesar in Lig. 5 35 and Phil. ii. 5 116 : and may be illustrated by the story of a lawsuit in which the defendant, one of Caesar's veterans, reminds him of a trifling incident in his Spanish wars (Seneca, de benef. ν. 24), he had sprained his ankle and was testing in a rough place on the march, and the soldier had brought him water in his helmet.
